            {
                "title": "Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)",
                "note": [
                    "Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) is a loop-prevention network protocol that allows for redundancy while creating a loop-free Layer 2 topology using blocked ports.",
                    "",
                    "![Image](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/syukrimokhtar/eswitching/main/serve/notes/T4-STP.png)",
                    "",
                    "**Steps to a Loop-Free Topology**",
                    "1. Elect the root bridge.",
                    "2. Elect the root ports.",
                    "3. Elect designated ports.",
                    "4. Elect alternate (blocked) ports",
                    "",
                    "**Elect the root bridge**",
                    " - The switch with the **lowest BID/lowest priority** will become the root bridge.",
                    " - If the priorities are the same, the switch with the **lowest MAC Address** will become the root bridge.",
                    "",
                    "![Image](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/syukrimokhtar/eswitching/main/serve/notes/T4-Bridge.png)"
                    
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol",
                "note": [
                    "<ul>",
                    "<li>Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP) is an evolution of STP that provides faster convergence than STP.</li>",
                    "<li>If a port is configured to be an alternate port it can immediately change to a forwarding state without waiting for the network to converge.</li>",
                    "</ul>"
                ]
            },
